article.description:
Crystal Robinson matched her season-high with 22 points and
Tamika Whitmore added 17 as the Liberty dominated the Connecticut
Sun 90-64 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Liberty win first game without Hammon
article.linkText: Liberty have few problems in rout of Sun
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty are looking for a new leading scorer and they suddenly have a handful of candidates. Crystal Robinson matched her season-high with 22 points and Tamika Whitmore added 17 as the Liberty dominated the Connecticut Sun 90-64 Tuesday night. New York won in its first game since losing leading scorer Becky Hammon to a season-ending ACL injury last Wednesday. Robinson had a career-high six assists, Whitmore grabbed six rebounds and Tari Phillips added 13 points and seven rebounds for the Liberty, who shot 62 percent from the field and outrebounded the Sun 35-19. "I wanted a couple of people to pick it up," Liberty coach Richie Adubato said. "Sixty-two percent? Obviously, they all decided to pick it up. "Life is good when you're making every shot." It was the most points for the Liberty since they scored 92 at Los Angeles in 1998, and the most ever New York has scored at home. Nykesha Sales tied a season-high with 26 points for Connecticut, which lost its third straight and fifth of six. Sales set her career-high with six 3-pointers, but no other Connecticut player scored in double figures. "We haven't been around. You're talking about a team that's been in the finals a lot," Connecticut coach Mike Thibault said, adding that his team has a lot of work to do. "It's not just one thing." Playing without Hammon, who was the first player off New York's bench, Adubato looked to Robinson and Vickie Johnson to provide offensive spark, but everyone got in on the act. Johnson had four points and two assists as New York scored the game's first 10 points. The Liberty hit 12 of their first 15 shots and outrebounded the Sun 20-7 in the first half, and that included three easy loose balls Connecticut picked up in the final minutes. "When we get off to a start like that, it brings out an emotional side to us," said Teresa Weatherspoon, who had a season-high seven assists. "That was the key: Everyone was confident." Sales scored five points and Shannon Johnson had four as the Sun cut the lead to 17-11, but Robinson hit three jumpers and a free throw to restore the double-digit lead at 24-13. "It was an emotional game," said Robinson, who nearly didn't play because of a right ankle injury. "If I could have foreseen that (performance), I'd be rich. I'd win the lottery." When New York's starters sat, the Liberty's reserves stepped up. Point guard Kristin Sharp outran and outdribbled Johnson and Sun reserve Debbie Black, Elena Baranova scored all of her 10 points in the second half, Linda Frohlich scored a career-high eight points and rookie Erin Thorn was productive while playing a career-high 18 minutes. "There was emotion out there," said Whitmore, who screamed and pumped her fists as the Liberty's lead grew. "At some point you have to get tired of winning one, losing one; winning one, losing one. You have to put together a string of wins." New York took advantage of Connecticut's sloppy ballhandling in the second half and pushed the lead to more than 20 points. When the Sun finally made a run, Baranova hit two 3s and Lindsey Yamasaki added another to push New York's lead to 72-51.

Game notes
The teams meet again Sunday in Connecticut. ... Sun F Taj McWilliams-Franklin played with a wrapped right shoulder after straining it in the Sting's 69-55 loss to Charlotte last Saturday. ... The Liberty set a season high with 47 first-half points. ... Weatherspoon had "25 Hammon" written on her shoes for her injured teammate, who had been playing some point guard and taking some of 'Spoon's minutes. Hammon was on the bench and limped out to greet teammates during timeouts.
